Projects

Cyclistic - The bike sharing company

A Google case study analysis using mySQL for merging historical data, then using Python to clean and manipulate data finishing with fact-finding visualization.

cyclistic

Summary¶

  • Launch in 2016

  • The program has grown to a fleet of 5,524 bicycles

  • Geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago

  • Marketing strategy was to build general awereness to a broad consumer segment

  • Pricing plan has two options:

    • casual riders: single-ride or full-day passes
    • annual membership

Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, the team believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be the key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, there might be a very good chance to convert casual riders into members. The problem is that the casual riders are already aware of the services and have already chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

The business task¶

Key stakeholders: Lily Moreno (The director of marketing and the manager), Cyclistic marketing analytics team and the Cyclistic executive team

Clear goal is to design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics.

There are three questions that will guide the future marketing program:

  1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?
  2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships?
  3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?

My scope would be to analyze the first question with the previous 12 months of Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

**** Disclaimer ****¶

Cyclisist is a fictional company. For the sole purpose of this case study the historical dataset is appropriate and can be used to answer the business questions. Nevertheless, the owner of the dataset is Motivate International Inc. under this licence. Motivate International Inc. disclaims any warranty that data will meet your needs or will be or continue to be available, complete, accurate, timely, secure or error free.

The data¶

This dataset is ROCCC:

  • Reliable, Original and Cited: complete time series, which are accurate for the task and is non-bias. We will treat them as second-party datasets from a reliable organization.
  • Current and Comprehensive: we consider them as regularly refreshed datasets, which are appropriate and will enable us to answer the business questions.

Data has been downloaded and stored locally and uploaded into Google Drive as a back-up.

I wasn't able to choose the quarterly files, because the latest was back in 2020, so I downloaded the monthly versions in csv from March of 2022 until February 2023.

These files are structured and organized in 13 columns without indicies including quantitative and qualitative data.

I'm using MySQL to combine data into one file from multiple csv files. Then I'm going to use MySQL connector to bring the data into Python to clean, manipulate and analyze the data with some detailed visualizations.

In [ ]:
import mysql.connector
			import csv
			import sys
			
			db = mysql.connector.connect(
			  host='localhost',
			  user='root',
			  password='*********',
			  database='cyclistic'
			)
			
			cursor = db.cursor()
			
			query = 'SELECT * FROM data'
			
			csv_path = 'C:/Users/Betti/Desktop/case study/historical data/alldata.csv'
			
			try:
				cursor.execute(query)
				rows = cursor.fetchall()
			finally:
				db.close()
			
			# Continue only if there are rows returned.
			if rows:
				# New empty list called 'result'. This will be written to a file.
				result = list()
			
				# The row name is the first entry for each entity in the description tuple.
				column_names = list()
				for i in cursor.description:
					column_names.append(i[0])
			
				result.append(column_names)
				for row in rows:
					result.append(row)
			
				# Write result to file.
				with open(csv_path, 'w', newline='') as csvfile:
					csvwriter = csv.writer(csvfile, delimiter=',', quotechar='"', quoting=csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL)
					for row in result:
						csvwriter.writerow(row)
			else:
				sys.exit("No rows found for query: {}".format(query))

  • end_lng: the longtitude of the ending station
  • member_casual: the customer type (casual rider or annual member)

It looks like the annual members are riding for the same amount of time on the weekdays. This fact suggests that these customers have bought annual membership because they use the bikes for the same purpose each day - not like the casual riders. The lenght of the rides are increasing on weekends.

Clearly there is an increase with the casual riders as well on the weekends. At this time I'm not able to identify any other trend.

If there would be customer IDs, we could investigate what is the growth in usage on the weekends with the annual members. Would be interesting to check what causes the longer rides, for example if it's registered by the same customers. We may have annual members who are only riding for the weekends doing the same trips over and over again.

Nevertheless, we can check the distribution of the ride IDs per customer type which could give us some insight on this topic.

If we check the weekly usage (the number of rides), we can see a fascinating difference between the two customer types: the busiest for the annual members are the weekdays, and the casual riders tend to ride more on the weekends. This leads to the conclusion that the annual members are probably ride to and from work or running the same errands.

I see that the annual members are using the service less on Mondays and Fridays. This is probably Monday Sickness and Friday Feaver! On Saturdays and Sundays they ride the minimum, don't really using the bikes on Sundays.

Would be interesting to check the working from home / hibrid working models in Chicago, if there is any correlation between the two data.

For the casual riders Saturdays are the most busiest days, followed by Sundays and Fridays with an average of decreasing tendency for the rest of the week. Our goal would be to increase the weekday usages especially in the warmer months.

If we check the distribution of the weekly ride lengths, we should notice that they are not develop the same amount of usage in minutes than in the number of rides - it's quite the opposite tendency.

For the annual members the duration can be divided into two groups: duration for the weekdays and on the weekends, with an increased usage on the weekends. This means that the distance is the same therefore the purpuse of the usage is the same depending on what days do they use the service. However, they don't like riding on Sundays. If they do, they probably go to the same location as on Saturday (same ride length, different number of rides).

Regarding the casual members, the third quartile is around 25 minutes which we can clearly see in the chart as well from Fridays to Mondays. This means that the 75% of the casual riders are using the service longer than 25 minutes on these days. Below this the daily ride lengths are not differenciate significantly for the rest of the week. Therefore, on these days the 25% of these riders are using the bikes for less than 25 minutes.

We can definitely identify some trends with a strong correlation to the weather, since the willingness of riding a bike is strongly dependent of the good weather conditions. The Cyclistic company is based in Chicago, where the climate is similar to the Hungarian weather: January is the coldest month and July is the warmest.

Therefore, as we could expect, Q2 and Q3 are the busiest season and P12 and P01 are the weakest. Casual riders have steeper decrease throughout the year which starts with a peak at the warmest month (P07) and ends in the coldest (P01). This is probably in relation with the tourists as they tend to visit Chicago in the warmer months.

However, we can see in the annual members' chart that the busiest season is from P05 to P10, which is increasing to the middle when the weather is the warmest. Then it decreases similarly by 3 months: [P04, P11, P03] and [P12, P02, P01]. I believe it's grouped because of the similar weather conditions.

This willingness can be vsualized the best with the number of rides sorted by the period.

We can see two beautiful normal distribution. This type of distribution is a continuous probability distribution in which most data points cluster toward the middle of the range (the mean), while the rest taper off symmetrically toward either extreme. So for example if we check the annual members we can see that P11 and P04 has similar number of rides, because they are similar in weather temperatures.

We can investigate further in the yearly tendencies by checking the duration of the rides. Let's sort the charts by period to check if we see the same trends as we saw on the weekly analysis.

I don't detect any significant change throughout the year for neither of customers regarding the lenght of the rides.

Since the annual members are probably using the service for the same purpose and since the weather is a key to the usage, I expected very low discripancy between the warmer months and the colder months (~3 minutes).

As from my experience, the customers who are tend to ride bikes on the warmest days usually bear the coldest ones as well. (Especially because Chicago's average temperature in the winter is -3°C, which we can considerate mild, while in the summer is 29°C). Although, we can see a light normal distribution here as well throughout the year because of the weather. They are more likely to ride longer routes in the warmer months.

Nevertheless, the casual riders have a bigger difference (~10 minutes).

We can see the same tendency here as in the weekly chart: in the winter they tend to ride shorter routes (under 25 minutes). However, we don't see a normal distribution here as it's highly depending on the number of rides. This suggests that these riders are more impulsively using the service.

What is interesting is that the casual riders have more than twice the ride length as the annual members, which is probably because these riders are using the service for pleasure (f.e. site seeing).

Since the annual member is most probably using the bikes for the same route, can be clearly deduced that the same route will be faster with an electric bike.

Logically, it can happen that the casual riders are faster with their routes using the electric bikes over the classic ones as well.

In spite of that, the all time high is ultimately the docked bikes regarding the rides' duration. The fact that these casual riders are not prefer these type of bikes, while it still has the longest rides makes me feel that this is an impulsive action to choose docked bikes over any other type of transportation. This is most likely a tourist characteristic: they see the many docking stations all over Chicago and they want to use it. Also, of course it can mean that the residents are using the services occasionally (f.e. other transportation failed, traffic jam, fun activity).

This impulsivity might be the most important information we could get from this dataset. It means we can affect these impulsive behaviour with simple marketing tactics.

Summary¶

  • Annual members using the service with more occasions on weekdays for the same amount of time. The duration is higher on weekends.
    • This means that the distance is the same therefore the purpuse of the usage is the same depending on what days do they use the service.


  • Casual riders using the service more on the weekends. Saturdays are the most busiest days, followed by Sundays and Fridays with an average of decreasing tendency for the rest of the week. The 75% of these customers are riding longer than 25 minutes on these days. Below this the daily ride lengths are not differenciate significantly for the rest of the week.

  • The casual riders have more than twice the ride length as the annual members.



  • There is a strong correlation to the weather, since the willingness of riding a bike is strongly dependent of the good weather conditions (July is the warmest and January is the coldest month).
  • For annual members the busiest season is from P05 to P10, which is high when the weather is the warmest. Then it decreases similarly by 3 months: [P04, P11, P03] and [P12, P02, P01]. It's grouped because of the similar weather conditions (normal distribution).
  • They have a very low discripancy (~3 minutes) in duration between the warmer months and the colder months (~3 minutes). They are more likely to ride slightly longer routes in the warmer months.
  • Casual riders have steeper decrease throughout the year which starts with a peak at P07 and ends in P01 (difference is ~10 minutes).
  • In the winter they tend to ride shorter routes (under 25 minutes). There isn’t a normal distribution for the year as it’s highly depending on the number of rides. This suggests that these riders are more impulsively using the service.




  • Annual members are using electrical and classic bikes, but they prefer the classic bikes.
  • Casual riders are the opposite.
  • They also use docked bikes in a very low amount of occasions, while it still has the longest rides. This is an impulsive action.

    • Suggestion¶

    1. New passes for members based on current usage:¶

    • Weekend passes from Friday to Sunday (72HR)
    • Weekly passes (WP)
    • Monthly passes (MP)
    • Quarterly passes (QP)
    • Half-year passes (HP)

    2. Pricing is better if bigger passes are chosen:¶

    • Single-ride is the most expensive

      • Guide customers to use the service more.
    - __Slightly better pricing with the Full-day pass__ (Single x 1.3)

    Better deal for the whole day. (-> We can calculate the monthly price multiplying this with 30)

    - __Best price for the 72HR__ (Full day x 1.5)

    Encourage casual riders to buy passes for the period they most likely riding.

    - __Just slightly more expensive for WP__ (72HR x 3)

    Sounds a better deal then the weekend pass, but not too aggressive tactic.

    - __More expensive for MP__ (Full day x 28)

    Intermediate option, not favorable

    - __QPs are better__ (MP x 2)

    Complementary 1 month if you choose bigger pass.

    - __HPs are even better__ (MP x 4)

    Complementary 2 month if you choose bigger pass.

    - __Annual passes are good__ (MP x 9)

    Complementary 3 month if you choose bigger pass.

    3. Get more insight¶

    Complementary Single-ride pass if a questionnaire is filled out (answering sex, age, location, contact info).


    This way we could further analyze the customer habits and define overall better strategies.
